<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900502-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>900502-0010.</DOCID><HL>   Ames Gets Court Approval   To Pay Pistner $2 Million</HL><DATE>05/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   ADD</CO><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><LP>   ROCKY HILL, Conn -- Ames Department Stores Inc., whichfiled for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 ofthe U.S. Bankruptcy Code, may be short on cash. But it'sproving generous to Stephen Pistner, its new co-chairman andchief executive officer.   Yesterday, Ames received approval from a U.S. bankruptcycourt judge in Manhattan to pay Mr. Pistner more than $2million for the first year of his services. That includes asigning bonus of $500,000 to be paid over the first sixmonths and an annual salary of $1.5 million. In addition Mr.Pistner gets reimbursed for travel, legal and otherincidental expenses.</LP><TEXT>   Creditors, many of whom were in the court, apparentlyapproved of the new leader's salary. &quot;If he's the right man,so be it,&quot; commented Wilbur Ross, a senior managing directorfor Rothschild's Inc., financial adviser to a number of bondholders and creditors. &quot;The task at hand is great and for ajob well done that would be small price to pay.&quot;   Mr. Pistner's appointment was approved at least on atemporary basis by the bankruptcy court. The action enablesMr. Pistner to serve in the two positions and holddiscussions with the retailer's creditors through May 19.Though yesterday's approval is only temporary, courtobservers said that a permanent approval is likely to follow.</TEXT></DOC>